The paper deals with self-adjusting binary search trees (BSTs) and their properties, which are a fundamental data structure in computer science. The paper proposes a global view of BST algorithms and identifies general structural properties of algorithms that satisfy the access lemma. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses a geometric view of how BST algorithms rearrange the search path, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of potential functions, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. The paper also presents a new family of algorithms based on ""strict"" depth-halving, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the amortized access cost for the path-balance heuristic, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-category.
